      "source": [
        "Euler's key step was to identify the same function in a different setting: the constant that appears when you differentiate $a^x$.\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\frac{d}{dx}a^x=(\\ln a)\\,a^x,\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "\\ln a=\\log_e a,\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "\\lim_{h\\to 0}\\frac{a^h-1}{h}=\\int_1^a \\frac{1}{t}\\,dt.$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Although the symbol $\\ln$ was introduced later, it represents the same logarithmic function that Euler identified. Once $e$ is chosen so that $\\ln e=1$, the special case becomes\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\ln e = 1,\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "\\frac{d}{dx}e^x=e^x,\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "\\frac{d}{dx}\\ln x=\\frac1x.$$\n",
        "\n",
        "No other base gives this clean a pair of relationships — every other exponential drags along an extra factor of $\\ln a$. Base 10 was convenient because we have ten fingers; base $e$ was, in Euler's hands, the base calculus itself pointed to.\n",
        "\n",
        "This is the shape of the story as it is usually retold today, with the pieces arranged for clarity. Euler's actual notebooks show the ideas arriving more gradually, tangled up with his broader work on infinite series, complex numbers, and trigonometry. But the destination was the same: Napier's computational shortcut, Bernoulli's compound-interest limit, and Euler's calculus of exponentials all turned out to describe one and the same number.\n",
        "\n",
        "For the first time, the pieces that had accumulated over more than a century finally fit together.\n",
        "\n",
        "```mermaid\n",
