        "    --> 1624[\"<b>1624: Briggs's Base 10</b><br>Henry Briggs popularizes decimal (base-10) logarithms for manual calculations.\"]:::milestone\n",
        "    --> 1683[\"<b>1683: Bernoulli's Compound Interest</b><br>Jacob Bernoulli discovers the limit of (1 + 1/n)ⁿ ≈ 2.71828 while analyzing interest growth.\"]:::milestone\n",
        "    --> 1697[\"<b>1697: Exponential Calculus</b><br>Johann Bernoulli studies exponential functions and their derivatives using calculus.\"]:::milestone\n",
        "    --> 1727[\"<b>1727: Euler Names 'e'</b><br>Leonhard Euler adopts the letter e for the constant and proves its unique calculus property.\"]:::milestone\n",
        "    --> 1748[\"<b>1748: The Unification</b><br>Euler publishes <i>Introductio in Analysin Infinitorum</i>, unifying the limit, series, and calculus properties.\"]:::milestone\n",
